documents.t: Spaces are the foundation of TabNest's organization system. Think of them as independent workspaces, each with its own set of tab groups and saved tabs.
Tab Groups are collections of related tabs within a Space. They allow you to further organize your work by topic, task, or any logical grouping.

We're excited to announce the release of TabNest v0.1.4 with major improvements and new features!

AI-Powered Categorization - Automatically organize tabs using multiple AI providers (Claude, OpenAI, Bailian) Cloud Sync - Sync your tabs to GitHub Gist or WebDAV Global Search - Instantly find any tab across all your Spaces Dark Mode - Beautiful dark theme with system preference support Multi-language - Support for English and Simplified Chinese
Fixed tab ordering issues Improved performance with large collections Enhanced keyboard navigation Better error handling
30% faster load times Reduced memory usage Optimized storage operations Smoother animations
Install TabNest from Chrome Web Store Create your first Space Start saving and organizing your tabs!
We'd love to hear your feedback! Please visit our GitHub Issues page to report bugs or suggest features.
Thanks to all our users and contributors who helped make this release possible!

Docusaurus blogging features are powered by the blog plugin. Here are a few tips you might find useful. Simply add Markdown files (or folders) to the blog directory. Regular blog authors can be added to authors.yml. The blog post date can be extracted from filenames, such as: 2019-05-30-welcome.md 2019-05-30-welcome/index.md A blog post folder can be convenient to co-locate blog post images: The blog supports tags as well! And if you don't want a blog: just delete this directory, and use blog: false in your Docusaurus config.

TabNest features intelligent AI-powered tab categorization that can automatically organize your tabs into meaningful groups. This is perfect for those moments when you have dozens of open tabs and need help bringing order to the chaos.

The AI categorization system uses advanced language models to: Read the title and URL of each tab Understand the content and purpose Suggest logical groupings and names Create organized tab groups automatically
Model: claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929 Setup: Requires Anthropic API key Best for: High-quality, context-aware categorization Cost: Pay-per-token
Default: SiliconFlow GLM-4.5-Air Setup: Provide API endpoint URL Best for: Cost-effective, reliable Supports: Custom endpoints (Local LLMs, Ollama, etc.)
Model: qwen-plus-latest Setup: Requires Bailian API key Best for: Chinese content Cost: Pay-per-token

For Claude (Recommended): Visit Anthropic Console Sign up for an account Create an API key Copy the key For OpenAI-Compatible Services: Visit SiliconFlow or use your own service Create an account Get your API key Note the API endpoint URL

Click TabNest icon ‚Üí Settings (gear icon) Navigate to AI Configuration Click "+ Add AI Provider" Fill in: Provider: Select from dropdown API Key: Paste your key Model ID: (auto-filled, can modify) API URL: (for OpenAI-compatible only) Click "Test Connection" to verify Click "Save"
In Settings ‚Üí AI Configuration Find your configured provider Click the radio button to set as default Multiple providers? No problem‚Äîyou can switch anytime

Save multiple tabs you want to organize Click the ‚ö° AI Smart Categorize button (lightning icon) Click "Start Categorization" Watch as the AI: Analyzes your tabs Streams suggestions in real-time Creates tab groups automatically Review the results: Accept the categorization ‚Üí "Apply" Reject and try again ‚Üí "Cancel"
The AI responses stream in real-time, so you see results appearing as they're generated. This is especially impressive with complex tab collections.

Before the categorization is finalized, you can: Edit group names - Click to rename groups Reorganize tabs - Drag tabs between suggested groups Merge groups - Combine similar groups Split groups - Separate large groups Then click "Apply" to finalize.

For best results: Use descriptive page titles - Sites with good titles categorize better Group related tabs - Don't mix completely different topics Use multiple calls - If results aren't perfect, refine and try again Provide context - Add a note about the project if needed

Some providers allow custom categorization prompts: Go to Settings ‚Üí AI Configuration Find your provider Look for "Custom Prompt" option Edit to specify your preferences: "Group by technology stack" "Group by urgency" "Group by document type"

If you don't like the categorization: TabNest automatically creates a backup before applying changes Go to Settings ‚Üí Data Management Click "Undo Last AI Categorization" Your previous tab organization is restored

Your data: Only tab titles and URLs are sent to AI providers Not stored: TabNest doesn't store categorization history Your control: You can review and modify results before applying Local first: All categorization happens after your approval
Encrypted: API keys are encrypted locally Never shared: Keys are never sent to TabNest servers Full control: You manage your own API keys and billing

Provider Cost Model Typical Cost Claude $0.003-0.03 per 1K tokens $0.05-0.15 per categorization SiliconFlow (OpenAI-compatible) $0.002 per 1K input tokens $0.01-0.05 per categorization Bailian Pay-per-call $0.01-0.05 per call

Batch categorizations - Do multiple tabs at once Monitor usage - Check your provider's dashboard regularly Use local LLMs - For advanced users: run local models via Ollama Test first - Use a small tab set before large operations

Keep your tab collection safe and accessible across devices with cloud synchronization. TabNest supports two popular cloud storage options.

Pros: Free Version history maintained Backed by trusted GitHub Private gists available Easy to share if needed Cons: Requires GitHub account Manual sync (with auto-sync available) 1MB file size limit per gist Best for: Developers, version control enthusiasts

TabNest's powerful global search feature lets you find any saved tab across all your Spaces and Tab Groups in seconds.
documents.s: Global Search - Find Any Tab Instantly

documents.t: Press Cmd+F (Mac) or Ctrl+F (Windows/Linux) to open the search dialog.
Open TabNest dashboard Click the üîç Search button in the top toolbar Start typing to search
Simply type keywords and TabNest will search: Tab titles - The name of the website or page URLs - The web address Both - Matching against either title or URL
Type a simple keyword: react - Find all tabs related to React api - Find API documentation github - Find GitHub links
You can combine multiple keywords: react tutorial - Find tabs containing both "react" and "tutorial" Use spaces to add more conditions
Results appear instantly as you type: Click any result to open the tab See which Space and Group the tab is in Multiple matches are ranked by relevance
In Settings, you can configure: Search scope - Search all Spaces or current Space only Case sensitivity - Match exact capitalization URL only - Search only URLs, not titles
If you have duplicate tabs: Search for a unique part of the URL Check if multiple results appear Delete duplicates to clean up
Use search as a quick way to navigate: Don't remember which Space something is in? Search for it instead of manually browsing Click the result to jump there
After searching, you can: Bulk select search results Move them to a different Group Delete them all at once
Search is case-insensitive by default Searches the last 100 characters of URL Can't search by metadata (date, color, etc.)
Spaces are the foundation of TabNest's organization system. Think of them as independent workspaces, each with its own set of tab groups and saved tabs.

A Space is a container that helps you organize tabs by project, context, or any categorization that makes sense to you. For example: Work projects (Frontend, Backend, Design) Personal interests (Learning, Shopping, Entertainment) Time-based contexts (Q4 2024 Goals, Research Project A)
Open TabNest and look at the left sidebar Click the "+" button at the top of the Space list Enter a name for your Space (Optional) Select an emoji icon for quick visual recognition Click "Create"
You can also use the keyboard shortcut to quickly open the creation dialog (settings configurable).
Right-click on a Space name Select "Rename" Enter the new name Press Enter or click away
Click on a Space name to select it Look for the icon in the Space header Click to open the emoji picker Select your preferred emoji
‚ö†Ô∏è Warning: This action cannot be undone! Right-click on a Space Select "Delete" Confirm the deletion Note: All tab groups and tabs in the Space will be deleted.
Click any Space name in the left sidebar to switch to it. The main area will update to show that Space's tab groups and tabs.
TabNest remembers which Space you were viewing last. When you reopen the extension, it will automatically show that Space.
Drag and drop Spaces in the left sidebar to reorganize them in your preferred order.
Use clear, descriptive names (e.g., "Frontend Dev" instead of "Project 1") Consider using prefixes for quick scanning (e.g., "üìö Learning", "üíº Work") Keep names concise (15-20 characters ideal)

By Project: One Space per project Great for developers and designers Example: "E-commerce Site", "Mobile App", "Documentation" By Context: Organize by time (Current Sprint, Next Quarter) Or by activity (Research, Planning, Execution) Useful for project managers By Domain: One Space per work domain Example: "Marketing", "Engineering", "Operations" Works well for larger teams

If you have two Spaces you'd like to combine: Open the Space you want to merge from Select all tab groups (use Ctrl+A or manually select) Cut the groups (Ctrl+X) Switch to the destination Space Paste (Ctrl+V) Or use the Merge Spaces feature (if available in Settings): Go to Settings ‚Üí Data Management Look for "Merge Spaces" option Follow the dialog to combine Spaces

If you have a very organized tab group that deserves its own Space: Select the tab group Right-click and select "Convert to Space" A new Space will be created with the group's contents The original tab group will be removed
Each Space's data is stored locally in your browser. You can sync Spaces to the cloud: See Cloud Sync for GitHub Gist or WebDAV setup All Spaces are included in cloud backups
Tab Groups are collections of related tabs within a Space. They allow you to further organize your work by topic, task, or any logical grouping.
Select a Space from the left sidebar In the main area, click "+ Add Group" Enter a group name (e.g., "APIs to Read", "Design References") (Optional) Choose a color and icon Click "Create"
Save multiple tabs to a Space Right-click a saved tab Select "Move to New Group" Enter the group name

Each group can have a color for visual organization: Blue - API References, Documentation Green - Active Projects, In Progress Yellow - To Review, Important Red - High Priority, Urgent Purple - Learning, Research Gray - Archived, On Hold Click the color dot next to a group name to change it.
Similar to Spaces, groups can have emoji icons: üìö Documentation üé® Design Resources üîß Tools üìä Analytics üõ†Ô∏è Development üìù Notes Click the icon to open the emoji picker.

Open Single Tab: Click any tab card to open it in your browser Open All Tabs: Click the "Open All" button on a group header Opens all tabs in the group in new browser tabs Open in New Window: Ctrl+Click (or Cmd+Click on Mac) to open in a new window
Hover over a tab card Click the "X" button Confirm deletion Or right-click the tab and select "Remove".
Drag and drop tabs within a group or between groups to reorganize them.
Right-click on the group name Select "Rename" Enter the new name Press Enter Or double-click the group name to edit directly.
Click the arrow icon next to a group name to collapse or expand it. Useful when you have many groups and want to save space.
Right-click on a group Select "Duplicate" A copy will be created in the same Space
Right-click on a group Select "Move" Choose destination Space Click "Move" Or use drag and drop if the destination Space is visible.

Welcome to TabNest! This guide will help you get up and running in just a few minutes.

TabNest is a productivity tool that helps you save, organize, and manage your browser tabs efficiently. With TabNest, you can: Create multiple workspaces (Spaces) for different projects Group related tabs together with custom colors and icons Use AI to automatically categorize and organize your tabs Sync your data to the cloud using GitHub Gist or WebDAV Search across all your saved tabs instantly
